{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2c40212e-af4c-4872-bbfc-a15eafcb51db","content":"\n\nHere's how to connect your C# MCP server to the **MCP Inspector**:\n\n### 1. Run the Inspector\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n### 2. Configure the connection\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a published binary:\n\n- **Command:** `/path/to/YourServer`\n\n### 3. Click **Connect**\n\nThe Inspector will launch your process, communicate over stdin/stdout, and display available tools, resources, and prompts.\n\n### Tips\n\n- **Logging must go to `stderr`**, not `stdout` — stdout is the MCP JSON-RPC channel. Use `Console.Error.WriteLine()` or configure your logger to write to stderr.\n- You can click any discovered **tool** in the Inspector to invoke it with test inputs and see the response.\n- If your server needs environment variables, add them in the Inspector's **Environment Variables** section before connecting.\n- If using `dotnet run`, make sure the project builds cleanly first (`dotnet build`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d5ce18da-d08c-4016-82d1-460e46328d97","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive testing/debugging. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to explore their codebase. I can answer directly.","outputTokens":363},"id":"a2c3ef22-9fe1-4eb2-a47a-b6f575ddc680","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:15.849Z","parentId":"fa460cd5-feff-4f92-ad4c-a14e81a540e9"}
